Today we are happy to announce the release of Jest 30. This release features a substantial number of changes, fixes, and improvements. While it is one of the largest major releases of Jest ever, we admit that three years for a major release is too long. In the future, we are aiming to make more frequent major releases to keep Jest great for the next decade.

If you want to skip all the news and just get going, run npm install jest@^30.0.0 and follow the migration guide: Upgrading from Jest 29 to 30.

issue.title: frontend/backend: New product image not visible immediately ‚Äî cache key not invalidated
issue.body:
**Description**
When a new product image is uploaded, the frontend still shows the old (or no) image. Need to invalidate cache or supply new download key.

**Reproduction**

1. Upload new product image.
2. Refresh product page ‚Äî image still shows old version or doesn't appear.

**Expected**
New image visible immediately after upload.

**Actual**
Old or missing image continues to display.

**Possible causes**

* Image URLs are cached (CDN or browser) and use same filename / same presigned URL.
* Frontend uses a cached URL without busting query param.
* Server returns presigned URL that doesn't change.

**Suggested fixes**

* When image is updated, update filename (e.g., include UUID or timestamp), or append cache-busting query param `?v={timestamp}` to image URL.
* If using presigned URLs, generate a new presigned URL on upload and return it immediately in response.
* If using CDN, call CDN invalidation for that object on image replace.
* Ensure client re-fetches product image metadata after upload (e.g., update state with returned image URL rather than relying on stale cache).

**Example**

```js
// After successful upload, update local product image url:
setProduct(prev => ({ ...prev, imageUrl: `${newUrl}?v=${Date.now()}` }));
```

**Acceptance checklist**

* [ ] Upload returns fresh image URL
* [ ] Client updates displayed image on success
* [ ] Cache-busting or CDN invalidation implemented
* [ ] Integration test: upload -> immediately see new image

**Severity:** Medium
**Labels:** `frontend`, `backend`, `cache`, `bug`

## PR Reviewer Guide üîç Here are some key observations to aid the review process:

üß™ PR contains tests

Type Safety Response models expose fields typed as enums or specific types, but several aggregations and search results build dicts from raw SQL that may contain None or plain strings where enums are expected; verify pydantic serialization and ensure consistent typing (e.g., ContentType keys/values) to avoid runtime validation errors. ```python class ContentAggregationResponse(BaseModel): """Response model for content aggregations.""" content_type_distribution: Dict[ContentType, int] = Field(..., description="Distribution by content type") workflow_distribution: Dict[str, int] = Field(..., description="Distribution by workflow") source_file_distribution: Dict[str, int] = Field(..., description="Distribution by source file") page_range_stats: Dict[str, Any] = Field(..., description="Page number statistics") confidence_stats: Dict[str, Any] = Field(..., description="Confidence score statistics") content_length_stats: Dict[str, Any] = Field(..., description="Content length statistics") ```
Dependency IDs Built-in template dependencies reference job IDs by hardcoded strings that don't match actual generated job IDs; this likely breaks dependency resolution. Ensure dependency references map to created job IDs or use names/aliases resolved at instantiation. ```python content_processing_template = WorkflowTemplate( id="content_processing_workflow", name="Content Processing Workflow", description="Automated content processing with MinerU and cleanup", category="content", jobs=[ WorkflowJob( name="Process PDF Content", task_function="process_pdf_task", task_args=["${file_path}", "${user_id}"], schedule_type=ScheduleType.ONE_TIME, priority=JobPriority.HIGH ), WorkflowJob( name="Generate Embeddings", task_function="generate_embeddings_task", task_args=["${content_id}"], schedule_type=ScheduleType.ONE_TIME, dependencies=[JobDependency(job_id="process_pdf_content")], priority=JobPriority.NORMAL ), WorkflowJob( name="Cleanup Temporary Files", task_function="cleanup_temp_files_task", task_args=["${temp_directory}"], schedule_type=ScheduleType.ONE_TIME, dependencies=[JobDependency(job_id="generate_embeddings")], priority=JobPriority.LOW ) ], ```
SQL Dialect Compatibility Queries use json_extract_path_text and ::int casting; confirm the target DB is PostgreSQL and adjust to jsonb operators (e.g., (event_data->>'results_count')::int) to prevent runtime SQL errors with SQLAlchemy/Postgres. ```python search_types_query = select( func.json_extract_path_text(AnalyticsEvent.event_data, 'search_type').label('search_type'), func.count(AnalyticsEvent.id).label('count') ).where( and_( AnalyticsEvent.event_type == EventType.SEARCH_QUERY, AnalyticsEvent.timestamp >= start_date, AnalyticsEvent.timestamp <= end_date ) ).group_by('search_type') search_types_result = await db.execute(search_types_query) search_types = { row[0] or "unknown": row[1] for row in search_types_result.all() } # No results queries no_results_query = select( func.json_extract_path_text(AnalyticsEvent.event_data, 'query_text').label('query'), func.count(AnalyticsEvent.id).label('count') ).where( and_( AnalyticsEvent.event_type == EventType.SEARCH_QUERY, AnalyticsEvent.timestamp >= start_date, AnalyticsEvent.timestamp <= end_date, func.json_extract_path_text(AnalyticsEvent.event_data, 'results_count')::int == 0 ) ).group_by('query').order_by(desc('count')).limit(20) no_results_result = await db.execute(no_results_query) no_results_queries = [ {"query": row[0], "count": row[1]} for row in no_results_result.all() ] ```

issue.title: Modernize the integration
issue.body:
This makes use of all the recent changes in the integration.

Some clarifications here:

1.  CONF_ALBUM_ART_TEMPLATE does nothing.  Users should be using CONF_ENTITY_PICTURE_TEMPLATE
2.  ATTR_ENTITY_ID was deprecated upstream almost 5 years ago.  It also does nothing.

I kept both of them in to avoid breaking configurations.

There may be some unforseen behavior changes because the previous version of this integration had outdated ways of updating states.

This new code heavily relies on the upstream MediaPlayer entity to handle all the heavy lifting.  Because of that, we are using the under the hood attributes to set all properties on the object.  This should provide a better user experience with the entity but it may change behavior.

Some new behavior is inherently added as well:

1.  `this` will work in all scripts.
2. `friendly_name` now accepts templates
3. availability behavior will now be consistent with all other template entities.
4. You can now set the state to `None` and the entity will go `unknown`.

In regards to development benefits;
1.  Optimistic states can be added rather easily.
2. New scripts/templates would be easy to add without heavy changes.

issue.title: replace training.Model with Model | [BUG]: Getting AttributeError: 'K‚Ä¶
issue.body:
[BUG]: Getting AttributeError: 'KerasHistory' object has no attribute 'layer' when calling DeepFace.represent with detector_backend="retinaface"

## Tickets

https://github.com/serengil/deepface/issues/1506

### What has been done

**from tensorflow.python.keras.engine import training
model = training.Model(img_input, x, name="ResNet34")**

TensorFlow considers anything under tensorflow.python.* a private/internal API. These APIs are not guaranteed to remain stable and may be blocked or unreliable‚Äîeven if the file exists.

The public, stable interface is tf.keras.models.Model (or similarly, keras.models.Model in standalone Keras)
which is fully supported across all TensorFlow versions (1.x via standalone Keras, and 2.x via tf.keras)

now its should be updated as

**model = Model(img_input, x, name="ResNet34")
and should remove imports
from keras.engine import training
from tensorflow.python.keras.engine import training**

comment.body:
Nope.. This is not about ArcFace Model issue. it is about how we load ArcFace model.

TensorFlow recommend to load model using **from tensorflow.keras.models import Model**
but we were still using old method **from tensorflow.python.keras.engine import training**
